PRE-MARKET JAPANESE AND SOUTH KOREAN STOCK NEWS: Z Holdings and Line announce merger deal
content:
JAPAN

Square Enix Holdings (9684 JT) - Co. noted its Dragon Quest Walk game received 10mln downloads which is up from more than 5mln in late September. (Newswires)

SoftBank (9984 JT) - Co. is said to have raised around USD 2bln for its Second Vision Fund and will begin operations by investing in startups. (Newswires)

Unizo Holdings (3258 JT) - Co. maintains position of JPY 5000/Shr offer for Fortress and wants talks to continue. (Newswires)

Yahoo Japan (4689 JT) - Co. operator Z Holdings which is a unit of SoftBank (9984 JT), announced merger deal with Naver (035420 KS) unit Line Corp (3938 JT). Reports noted Line will become SoftBank's consolidated unit and that they proposed taking Line private for JPY 5200/Shr, while they were said to plan to keep Line Pay and PayPay separate for the time being. (Newswires)

 

SOUTH KOREA

Hanwha Aerospace (012450 KS) - Co. awarded KRW 351bln engine parts order from GE (GE). (Newswires)

Other News - US and South Korea have postponed joint military drills to help provide an opportunity to bring North Korea back to negotiations, although other reports noted that North Korea proceeded with air drills despite efforts by US and South Korea to reduce tensions. (Newswires/SCMP)

PRE-MARKET AUSTRALIAN STOCK NEWS: Saracen Mineral (SAR AT) agrees to acquire Barrick Gold’s 50% interest in Kalgoorlie Consolidated Gold Mines JV for about USD 750mln
content:
Resolute Mining (RSG AT) - Co. affirms FY19 output guidance at 400k ounces of gold at all-in sustaining cost of USD 1020 per ounce. (Newswires)

Saracen Mineral (SAR AT) - Co. agrees to acquire Barrick Gold’s 50% interest in Kalgoorlie Consolidated Gold Mines JV for about USD 750mln and will raise USD 796mln through institutional placement. (Newswires)

Seven West Media (SWM AT) - Prime Media has been told that merger transaction deal with Seven West is unfair but independent expert added that it is still in the best interest if there is no better offer. (The Australian)

Suncorp (SUN AT) - Co. reported total lending contracted 0.6% during the September quarter, while it expects ongoing competitive pressure for home loan refinancing options for H2 FY20, Co. also announced strategic investment in peer-to-peer platform Car Next Door. (Newswires)

Energy - WTI crude futures gained 2% on Friday to test the USD 58.00/bbl level to the upside. (Newswires)

Other News - Australia’s Human Right Technical Co-operation program with China was suspended. (Newswires)

DAILY ASIA-PAC OPENING NEWS
content:
ASIA-PAC

US Treasury Secretary Mnuchin and US Trade Representative Lighthizer conducted a phone call with Chinese Vice Premier Liu He on Saturday in which they were said to have held "constructive discussions" on each other's core concerns and agreed to maintain close communication. (Newswires)

US Commerce Secretary Ross said the finish line is close regarding a China Phase One Trade Deal on paper, while he added the important thing is to make sure that the deal is what we think it is and make sure that it is consistent with the promises that they’ve made to us. (Fox/Twitter)

US Commerce Secretary Ross said US President Trump has not yet indicated any change on the December 15 China tariffs thus far but there is plenty of time and stated if there is no base for the deal, there will be no tariff rollback. Ross added the question is whether or not China will commit to USD 40-50bln worth of agricultural purchases or will try and find a way out, while he also reiterated the view that Huawei is not an acceptable candidate to run US 5G services but added a US-China deal will be made in all likelihood and thinks there is a very high probability. (Newswires)

Industry experts said that US President Trump’s request for USD 50bln farm deal with China is not possible in practice following trade war related market shift. (SCMP)

US government is reportedly preparing to extend licences to allow US companies to use Huawei equipment. (NYT)

PBoC quarterly monetary policy report stated China’s economy faces increasing downward pressure and more uncertainties but remains under control. (Newswires)

Hong Kong Government is to step up coordination between departments and take "more decisive measures" to end the violence, while further clashes were reported over the weekend in which police fired tear gas at protesters in the vicinity of a university campus and protesters set fire to main entrance of a university as police attempted to move in. (Newswires)

  • New Zealand Performance of Services Index (Oct) 55.4 (Prev. 54.4). (Newswires)
  • Indian Trade Balance (USD)(Oct) -11.01B vs. Exp. -12.05B (Prev. -10.86B)
  • Indian Exports (USD) (Oct) 26.38B (Prev. 26.03B)
  • Indian Imports (USD)(Oct) 37.39B (Prev. 36.89B)

 

UK/EU

UK Election Poll: Conservatives 43% (+3), Labour 30% (U/C), Liberal Democrats 15% (U/C), Brexit Party 5% (-3), Panelbase survey November 13th-14th. (Newswires)

UK Foreign Secretary Raab said he does not think it is remotely likely that the UK would Brexit without a Free Trade Agreement at the end of the transition period. (Newswires)

Brexit Party has reportedly stood down in 43 non-Conservative seats where the Conservatives came second in 17 of the seats and 11 of those are Labour, according to Telegraph's Rayner. (Twitter)

UK opposition Labour Party manifesto will include a windfall tax on oil companies as part of its attempts to shift the UK towards a low-carbon economy, according to the FT’s Chief Political Correspondent. (FT)

Incoming EU Council President Michel said EU is ready to negotiate with UK, but declined to predict how long a trade deal between the EU & UK would take. (Newswires)

ECB's Weidmann (Hawk) said he is not against expansionary policy but must weigh how much, while he suggested that interest rates are close to the lower bound and that Germany is not in a crisis. (Newswires)

ECB’s Muller (Hawk) suggested the central bank could do take even more unconventional measures if the situation becomes severe. (Newswires)

ECB's Visco said to raise inflation, monetary policy can do nothing but continue with non-standard measures which increases the risk of adverse side effects, while he added the European single currency needs to interact with a single fiscal policy. (Newswires)

Norwegian official said from what he understands following conversations with US Commerce Secretary Ross, the EU auto tariff decision has been delayed. (minE24)

S&P affirmed Iceland at A; Outlook Stable. (Newswires)

  • EU HICP Final (Oct) M/M 0.1% vs. Exp. 0.2% (Prev. 0.2%). (Newswires)
  • EU HICP Final (Oct) Y/Y 0.7% vs. Exp. 0.7% (Prev. 0.7%)

 

COMMODITIES

Baker Hughes (Nov. 15th) US rig count: oil rigs -10 at 674, nat gas rigs -1 at 129, total rigs -11 at 817. (Newswires)

IEA Monthly Oil Report maintained oil demand growth estimates for 2019 and 2020 at 1mln BPD and 1.2mln BPD respectively, while it noted that global oil supply rose 1.5mln BPD in October as Saudi Arabian production returned to normal and on increases from Norway, Canada and the US. (Newswires) 

 

US

US President Trump reiterated they will be carrying out major middle-income tax cuts. Trump also commented on healthcare and stated that reforms will have a "tremendous impact" on health care pricing which will lead to more competitive pricing and greater transparency, while he will be giving the US the right to purchase prescription drugs from other countries. (Newswires)

Fed's Brainard (Voter, Dove) said risk appetite appears in the middle of its historic range with corporate debt loads remaining historically high, but the financial sector is resilient with low overall leverage and funding risk. (Newswires)

Fed’s Daly (Non-Voter, Dove) said low inflation despite low unemployment creates an opportunity for the economy, while she added that accommodative policy can bring more workers into the labour force and push inflation back towards 2% inflation target level. (Newswires)

  • US Industrial Production (Oct) M/M -0.8% vs. Exp. -0.4% (Prev. -0.4%, Rev. -0.3%). (Newswires)
  • US Manufacturing Production (Oct) M/M -0.6% vs. Exp. -0.6% (Prev. -0.5%)
  • US Retail Sales (Oct) M/M 0.3% vs. Exp. 0.2% (Prev. -0.3%)
  • US Retail Sales Ex-Autos (Oct) M/M 0.2% vs. Exp. 0.4% (Prev. -0.1%)

 

MARKET RECAP

Healthcare stocks (HUM, UNH, CNC, ANTM) caught a bid in the afternoon as Trump formally announced the administration’s new healthcare price transparency plans, giving states the option to purchase drugs abroad also. Occidental Petroleum (OXY) legged higher amid Warren Buffet taking a new stake in the name; RH (RH) also surged following Buffett taking a new stake. Danaher (DHR) caught a bid as it announced its exchange offering plan for its divestment of Envista (NVST). Qualcomm (QCOM) and Baker Hughes (BKR) were on the front foot following upgrades at Mizuho and Susquehanna, whilst GrubHub (GRUB) found some reprieve after a double upgrade at Barclays on potential for a sale. CenterPoint Energy (CNP) took a hit after receiving less favourable terms than expected in a Texas Electric case, with several research houses downgrading the name. Lyft (LYFT) benefitted from a Top Pick mention at JPMorgan. Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) was supported from a PT rise at RBC. Johnson & Johnson (JNJ) was supported from an Oklahoma judge announcing it would be decreasing the fine it owes the state in the opioid case. T-Mobile (TMUS) saw some volatility on source reports denying that CEO John Legere would be leaving the Co. S&P 500 0.8% at 3120, NASDAQ-100 0.7% at 8316, Dow Jones 0.8% at 28005.

The TPLEX traded with mild losses to end the week, with the usual risk driver of positive US-China trade sentiment weighing on havens; yields were higher across the curve by approximately 2bps at settlement. On the week, yields have come off their recent highs, with the 10-year yield currently around 1.83%, compared to the 1.97% reached last week, where the yield rally has taken a breather this week, in addition to some more cautious trade updates providing some resistance to selling pressures. The slate of Fed speak has shown unanimous content with current policy and an FOMC on pause as it waits to see how the economy reacts to recent cuts; the 2s10s has narrowed from just shy of 27bps to 22bps. US T-note (Z9) futures settled 6+ ticks lower at 129.04+.
